      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>4-Dimethylaminopyridine (DMAP) acts as a catalyst in acyl transfer reactions. DMAP’s catalytic activity stems from its nucleophilic character at the pyridine nitrogen, not the dimethylamino group. Explain this behavior, taking resonance into account.</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down-30\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBbjhhIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--a85118657c87d91a833f0223845507b7210e43e7/OChem_24_EC_058.jpg\" alt=\"The structure of 4-dimethylaminopyridine. It has a pyridine ring linked to a nitrogen connected to two methyl groups.\">",
